        "content": "<p>When I want to model a scenario, I find ordered pairs to be paramount.</p>\n<p>In a system to be modeled, one often has some entities, and some relationships between them. Perhaps the relationships are functions, or maybe they don't meet the criteria of a function, in which case they are relations; and relations are defined in terms of products. It seems like all of our modeling needs can be reduced to having \"a category with products\".</p>\n<p>However, it seems like products have a kind of arbitariness. In modeling a system, the real reason we use ordered pairs is to track associations or correspondences. For example, let there be a collection of commodities and a collection of people. Each person owns some quantity of some commodities.</p>\n<p>I can model this in equivalent ways. I can form ordered pairs of commodities and quantities. A collection of such ordered pairs can represent a person who owns those commodities in those quantities. In this choice of modeling approach, we do not have a set of primitive elements called \"people\". We associate a person with what they own: <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Person</mtext><mo>⊆</mo><mtext>Commodities</mtext><mo>×</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\textrm{Person} \\subseteq \\textrm{Commodities} \\times \\mathbb{Q}^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8193em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Person</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7778em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Commodities</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.938em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. The \"representation of people\" is because we choose to name a set with the name of a person.</p>\n<p>We can also include people as primitive elements. We can form ordered triples associating a person with a commodity and with a quantity: <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>Person</mtext><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mtext>Commodity</mtext><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mtext>Quantity</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\textrm{Person}, \\textrm{Commodity}, \\textrm{Quantity})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Person</span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Commodity</span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Quantity</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>. Or, we could have chosen to first group commodities with quantities, then people with commodity-quantities: <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>Person</mtext><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>Commodity</mtext><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mtext>Quantity</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\textrm{Person}, (\\textrm{Commodity}, \\textrm{Quantity}))</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Person</span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Commodity</span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Quantity</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span></span></span></span>. Or, we could have represented ownership as a function, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>owns</mtext><mo>:</mo><mtext>People</mtext><mo>×</mo><mtext>Commodities</mtext><mo>→</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\textrm{owns}: \\textrm{People} \\times \\textrm{Commodities} \\to \\mathbb{Q}^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">owns</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">People</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Commodities</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.938em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>None of this matters, because all of the above representations have the same information. From the perspective of category theory, it seems like we are just forming products, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>People</mtext><mo>×</mo><mtext>Commodities</mtext><mo>×</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\textrm{People} \\times \\textrm{Commodities} \\times \\mathbb{Q}^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">People</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7778em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Commodities</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.938em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. Regarding universal properties, it seems like category theory helps us clear away surface details and find a canonical representation of structures. </p>\n<p>However, it makes me feel like we are using the fact that products form an order of elements as a heuristic to track correspondences. What I truly want is to preserve the information that \"Melissa owns 3 Bitcoins\". If my model represents ownership as a triple <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>People</mtext><mo>×</mo><mtext>Commodities</mtext><mo>×</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\textrm{People} \\times \\textrm{Commodities} \\times \\mathbb{Q}^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">People</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7778em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Commodities</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.938em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, then I have a standard format by which I can extract information from any ordered triple that comes my way. But the order of the elements was never the point. I could model the same information as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Commodities</mtext><mo>×</mo><mtext>People</mtext><mo>×</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\textrm{Commodities} \\times \\textrm{People} \\times \\mathbb{Q}^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7778em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Commodities</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">People</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.938em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>Is there an even better \"universal\" way to model this? </p>\n<hr>\n<p><em>My only idea has been to tag the type of the elements and define functions that seek out an element of that type, in an unordered set, as their argument. For example, consider a transaction to be changing the \"person\" element in an ownership-triple: <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>give</mtext><mo>:</mo><mtext>People</mtext><mo>×</mo><mtext>People</mtext><mo>×</mo><mtext>Commodity</mtext><mo>→</mo><mtext>People</mtext><mo>×</mo><mtext>Commodities</mtext><mo>×</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\textrm{give} : \\textrm{People} \\times \\textrm{People} \\times \\textrm{Commodity} \\to \\textrm{People} \\times \\textrm{Commodities} \\times \\mathbb{Q}^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8623em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">give</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">People</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">People</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Commodity</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">People</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7778em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Commodities</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.938em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. Specifying a giver, a receiver, and a commodity, you receive a new ownership triple for the new owner. Instead of relying on the order of elements in the tuples, we can tell the function what to do with the input data based on each element's type: <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mtext>Melissa : Giver</mtext><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mtext>Yosef : Receiver</mtext><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mtext>Ham : Commodity</mtext><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mtext>3.7 : Quantity</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{\\textrm{Melissa : Giver}, \\textrm{Yosef : Receiver}, \\textrm{Ham : Commodity}, \\textrm{3.7 : Quantity}\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Melissa : Giver</span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Yosef : Receiver</span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">Ham : Commodity</span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textrm\">3.7 : Quantity</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span>. I may also use spans as generalized relations.</em></p>",
        "id": 466097837,
        "sender_full_name": "Julius Hamilton",
        "timestamp": 1724959991
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>perhaps you are looking for so-called \"indexed products\", where the projections of an n-ary, unordered tuple are labelled by elements from an arbitrary set, rather than \"first\" and \"second\"?</p>",
        "id": 466101972,
        "sender_full_name": "Ryan Wisnesky",
        "timestamp": 1724961324
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's worth noting that your modeling alternatives are not all equivalent. If we say that P=People is a subset of CxQ (Commodity x Quantity), then we can't have two people with the same ownership profile, whereas taking a set of triples will allow this.</p>",
        "id": 466110768,
        "sender_full_name": "Spencer Breiner",
        "timestamp": 1724964679
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Of course, taking spans rather than relations addresses this issue</p>",
        "id": 466110807,
        "sender_full_name": "Spencer Breiner",
        "timestamp": 1724964705
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You may get some insight from looking at the way that undirected graphs are modeled as presheaves. Instead of getting rid of directed edges (as in the graph schema <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi><mo>⇉</mo><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E\\rightrightarrows V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8641em;vertical-align:-0.1808em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⇉</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span>), we associate an undirected edge with a pair of directed edges, related by an involution. This trick of adding in all (ordered) permutations to represent an unordered structure is pretty common.</p>",
        "id": 466111413,
        "sender_full_name": "Spencer Breiner",
        "timestamp": 1724964965
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can try the AlgebraicJulia blog for a <a href=\"https://blog.algebraicjulia.org/post/2020/09/cset-graphs-1/\">discussion of this approach</a>.</p>",
        "id": 466111560,
        "sender_full_name": "Spencer Breiner",
        "timestamp": 1724965069
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"281326\">Ryan Wisnesky</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Can.20we.20get.20rid.20of.20the.20arbitrariness.20of.20.22ordered.20pairs.22.3F/near/466101972\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>perhaps you are looking for so-called \"indexed products\", where the projections of an n-ary, unordered tuple are labelled by elements from an arbitrary set, rather than \"first\" and \"second\"?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Would you have a formal definition on hand?</p>",
        "id": 466138800,
        "sender_full_name": "Julius Hamilton",
        "timestamp": 1724981313
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Mendelson gives one standard definition of indexed products <a href=\"https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/3433468/cartesian-product-of-an-indexed-family-by-example\">here on Math Stackexchange</a>.</p>",
        "id": 466139752,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1724981963
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Given a set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span>, and a set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X_i</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0785em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> for each <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">i \\in I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6986em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span>, an element of the product</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mo>∏</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\prod_{i \\in I} X_i </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0771em;vertical-align:-0.3271em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">∏</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1786em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">∈</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3271em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0785em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>is a function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> that maps each <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">i \\in I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6986em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> to some element <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>∈</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x_i \\in X_i</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6891em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3117em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0785em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
