    {
        "content": "<p>This is all very interesting and I will be thinking about how to use the above ideas in my mathematical models.</p>",
        "id": 466144016,
        "sender_full_name": "Julius Hamilton",
        "timestamp": 1724984250
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok, so in a category, instead of having a product whose projection morphisms are <em>numbered</em>, we have projection morphisms that are indexed by <em>any</em> set. It looks like this is discussed in the article <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/family%20of%20sets\">[[family of sets]]</a>, and generalized in <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/dependent%20product\">[[dependent product]]</a>.</p>\n<p>Does anyone have an exercise or proof that can help me learn more about dependent products?</p>",
        "id": 466571509,
        "sender_full_name": "Julius Hamilton",
        "timestamp": 1725119943
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not so good at this stuff, but you can prove that if you have a category C that has finite products whose projections morphisms are <em>numbered</em>, then C also has finite products whose projection morphisms that are indexed by <em>any</em> finite set.</p>\n<p>(I'm putting a finiteness restriction in here just to make the problem easier to think about.  It's not necessary, but the concept of 'numbered' for infinite products requires using numbers that aren't finite, e.g. infinite ordinals, which is a distraction here, I think.)</p>",
        "id": 466576812,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1725122503
    }
]